{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_albatross_ver01/data/sn84020657/0027955064A/1914020301/0116.xml":{"full_text":"ALASKA DAILY EMPIRE\nPublished by the EMPIRE PRINTING COMPANY\nJOHN W. TROY, Editor and Manager.\nTelephone No. 3-7-4\nEntered as second-class matter November 7, 1912 at the postofilre at Ju\nneau. Alaska, under the Act of March 3. 1S79.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES:\nOre year, by mail 310.00\nSix months, by mail 5.00\nPer month, delivered 1.00\nONE YEAR'S ACCOMPLISH\nMENT.\nWHEN Speaker Clark said in\nthat Iowa speech the\nother night that the best\nyear's work that has been per\nformed at Washington in a gen\neration is nearing its end, he did\nnot speak idly. Before the first\ntwelve months of Wilson's ad\nministration shall have been\ncompleted, the Alaska railroad\nlegislation will probably have\nbeen added to the tariff and cur\nrency laws. It has not been of\nten that so much constructive\nlegislation has been accomplish\ned in one year by any Nation\nany where at any time.\nBut even that does not include\nall that the administration has\ndone in the line of progress. It\nhas abolished dollar diplomacy.\nIt has established a wider, bet\nter and more enlightened mean\ning for the Monroe doctrine.\nIt has increased the influ\nence of the United States for\npeace and for a higher plane\nof diplomacy. It has pur\nsued the enforcement of anti\ntrust legislation in such a way\nthat the co-operation of the\ntrusts themselves is being se\ncured for law-keeping. It has\ndestroyed completely the power\nof the Washington hired lobby.\nAnd all this is but a starter.\nAlready the leaders are working\nout further plans along lines'\nthat indicate that the second!\nyear of the administration will!\nsee as much accomplished for;\nprogress as was performed in\nthe first year. I\nSome of those women at\nWashington yesterday did their\nvery best?or worst?to prove\nto the President that he did right\nwhen he refused to assist them\nin securing a women suffrage\nconstitutional amendment.\nGermany has joined Great\nBritain in adding her weight to\nthe support of the American\nMexican policy. \"All things\ncome to him who waits.\"\nAN EXCELLENT PROMOTION\nTHE promotion of John F.\nPugh to the highest office\nin the United States cus\ntoms service in Alaska was a\nmeet recognition of faithful ser\nvice capably performed. It was,\nalso, the recognition of a real\nAlaskan, and a life-long Demo\ncrat. Mr. Pugh has lived nearly\nall the years of his manhood in\nAlaska. He had earned his right\nto be called an Alaskan some\ntime before he was appointed to\nthe customs service irom Skag\nway, and the record he has made\nin the Territory as an official and\na citizen formed the recommen\ndations which guided the Secre\ntary of the Treasury and the\nPresident in selecting him for\none of the principal offices at\nthe disposal of the administra\ntion in Alaska.\nThat Mr. Pugh's record at the\nhead of the customs service in\nthe North will amply justify the\nchoice of the appointing power\nnone who knows him doubts for\na single moment.\nTHE BUSINESS OUTLOOK.\nTHE opinion in the East is that\nthe business outlook at the\nend of January is better\nthan it was at the beginning of\nthe month, notwithstanding that\nthat it was optimistic then. It\nis conceded everywhere that sub\nstantial progress toward the\ngood time coming has been made\nsince the beginning of the year.\nEverywhere the disposition of\nbusiness men to accept the pofy'\ncies of the administration as thfe\nestablished policies of the Nap\ntion is apparent. It is conceded\nthat the new era has come to re\nmain, and business is fast accus\ntoming itself to work under the\nnew rules, and, strange as it\nmight seem, most of those doing\nbusiness are beginning to con\nfess a liking for the changed con\ndition.\nKermit should make a good\nDemocrat. His father has qual\nified as a \"first aid\" to Demo\ncrats^\nFAIRBANKS DEMOCRATS\nARE HARMONIOUSj\nHarmonic Hall was on Tuesday night\nthe scene of Democratis harmony such\nas President Wilson's own Cabinet\nmight envy. It is not thought by in\nquiring minds that the name of the\nhall bad anything to do with it either.\nThe 100 or more Democrats who were\npresent just naturally felt and acted\nthat way. J\nBefore they came together on Tues\nday evening it was rather expected in\nsome quarters that there would be\nfriction; that this one or that one\nwould take advantage of the occasion\nto remind someone else that he had\nnot been treated just right by the\nfellow members. But when they got\ntogether, all in one room, around one\nfiref too. the specter of discord failed\nto put in an appearance.\nIt was discovered that the Demo\ncrats of Fairbanks and vicinity had\nno quarrel with each other; that their\nonly enemies were the enemies of De\nmocracy and the administration which\nhas given it a new birth. It was found\nthat the members had each been Inoc\nulated with the Wilson spirit of \"the\ngreatest good to the greatest number.\"\nAH of this has a meaning. When\nDemocrats, supposed to have been as\nwidely separated as those of the Fair\nbanks district, suddenly present a\nsolid front, something is likely to fol\nlow. Something will follow, and that\nsomething will be a Democratic vic\ntory in Alaska in the next campaign.\nThe railroad is already assured, and\nnow the best way to show our appre\nciation to President Wilson for what\nhe has done in that direction would\nbe for the Democrats of Alaska to do\na few things.\nThe next time we trouble a busy\nman like Wilson with wires from the\nNorth, let it be to inform him that this\ntime we have something to give and\ni\nnot something to ask for.?Fairbanks\nCitizen.\n\"STROLLER\" WHITE COMING\nBACK TO GET EVEN\n\"Stroller\" E. J. White, of the White\nhorse Star, has written to those whom\nhe left in charge of his newspaper that\nhe will be back and on the job about\nFebruary 6th. He left the editorial\ncolumns of the Star in charge of a\npreacher when he departed from the\nNorth, and to him he apologizes for\nremaining away so long. He says he\nwill \"get even\" when he returns by\npreaching some Sunday evening for\nthe pastor.\nHEARST SECURES NEW\nRESIDENCE IN ARIZONA\nSAN FRANCISCO. Feb. 3.?William j\nRandolph Hearst has purchased a five\nacre tract on the rim of the Grand\nCanyon of Arizona and an adjoining\ntract of 155 acres. A lodge will be\nbuilt upon it and a great park creat\ned. which will be unlike any residen\ntial spot in existence.\nDon't forget the Juneau Athletic\nclub dance every Thursday evening at\nElks' hall. 2-3-tf.\nEVERY DAY\nA BIG DAY\nWe Bake Three Times Daily\nBread, Cakes, Pies,\nCakes to Order for\nSpecial Occasions\nEureka Bakery\n302 Franklin SL Phone 2122\n\nCOLLARS\nWE HAVE THE NEW STEAM-HEATED, COLLAR IRON\nING MACHINE. AND EMPLOY ONLY EXPERT OPERA\nTORS BOTH IN IRONING AND STARCHING OUR COL\nLARS. WE INVITE COMPARISON.\nALASKA STEAM LAUNDRY Inc.\nPhone?15 J. H. KIN G, Mgr.\nDUKE MAY BECOME\nCITIZEN OF BRITAIN\nLONDON, Feb. 3.?It Is rumored In\nLondon that James B. Duke^ the\nAmerican tobacco magnate, will be\ncome a British subject.\nIOWA \"BLUE SKY\nLAW\" IS VALID j\nDES MOINE8, Feb. 3. The Iowa\n\"blue sky law\" was upheld by tho J\nFederal Court In Des Moines against\nan attack by investment brokers of\nKansas City, St. Louis and New York\non the grounds of constitutionality. j\nROYAL FRUIT CO., Phone 280.~\nFresh ranch eggs by the dozen or\ncase.\nBurbanks potatoes?the best?by the\nsack or ton.\nROYAL FRUIT CO., Phone 280.\nA LETTER FOR YOU J\n\nList of letters remaining in the\npostofllce at Juneau, Alaska, on Jan.\n24, 1913. Parties wishing same, when J\ncalling please say \"advertised.\"\nBardon, R. (card)\nBirdscth. Mr.\nCalvin, E. F.\nCrawford, Ervie (card)\nChalland. H.\nClason, Jack (card)\nGalloway, Mr*\nGreen, F. (card)\nGertfh, Luoisa, Rudolf (card\nGeorge, Jack.\nHahm, James\nHaho, Abraham.\nHarvey, Tom\nHanrafty, Peter\nHenderland, Iver (card) J\nHeller, O. J. (card)\nHicks, Ja